      <!-- ═══ ACCESSIBILITY TAB ═══ -->
      <div class="tab-content" id="tab-accessibility" style="display: none; padding-top: 32px;">
        <h2 id="accessibility" class="doc-section-title">Accessibility</h2>
        <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Guidelines for ensuring Counter components are perceivable and understandable across all assistive technologies.</p>

        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="accessibility-guidelines" class="doc-h3">Accessibility Guidelines</h3>
          <table class="size-table">
            <thead><tr><th>Guideline</th><th>Requirement</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>aria-label</strong></td>
                <td>Required</td>
                <td>Provide full context, e.g., <code style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 13px; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 6px; background: rgba(37,99,235,0.06); color: var(--prism-violet);">aria-label="5 unread messages"</code> rather than just "5". The numeric value alone is insufficient for screen reader users.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Color Contrast</strong></td>
                <td>WCAG AA</td>
                <td>All Subtle and Intense combinations meet WCAG AA contrast minimums (4.5:1 for text). The Moderate/Intense variant uses black text (#000000) on yellow (#F9B21D) to maintain adequate contrast.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Screen Reader</strong></td>
                <td>Contextual announcement</td>
                <td>The count should be announced with context from the parent element. Use <code style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 13px; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 6px; background: rgba(37,99,235,0.06); color: var(--prism-violet);">aria-describedby</code> or wrap the counter within a labeled container so the relationship is clear.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Color Independence</strong></td>
                <td>Required</td>
                <td>Do not rely solely on color to convey the semantic state of a counter. Always provide additional context through labels, position, or descriptive text so that users who cannot perceive color differences still understand the meaning.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="contrast-ratios" class="doc-h3">Color Contrast Verification<span class="h3-badge" style="background: rgba(34,197,94,0.15); color: #16a34a;">WCAG AA Pass</span></h3>
          <p class="doc-section-subtitle">All Counter color combinations have been verified against WCAG 2.1 Level AA requirements.</p>

